│ The user wants me to fix a crash in the LLVM optimizer's loop vectorizer.                                                                                                                │
│ The crash is an assertion failure `!verifyFunction(...)` due to an "Instruction does not dominate all uses!" error. This indicates that the loop vectorizer is generating invalid LLVM   │
│ IR.                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The failing test case is `recurrence_phi_with_same_incoming_values_after_simplifications`.                                                                                               │
│ Let's analyze its structure:                                                                                                                                                             │
│ ```llvm                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ define i8 @recurrence_phi_with_same_incoming_values_after_simplifications(i8 %for.start, ptr %dst) {                                                                                     │
│ entry:                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│   br label %loop                                                                                                                                                                         │
│ loop:                                                                                                                                                                                    │
│   %iv = phi i32 [ 1, %entry ], [ %iv.next, %loop ]                                                                                                                                       │
│   %for = phi i8 [ %for.start, %entry ], [ %for.next, %loop ]                                                                                                                             │
│   %for.next = and i8 %for.start, -1                                                                                                                                                      │
│   ...                                                                                                                                                                                    │
│   br i1 %ec, label %exit, label %loop                                                                                                                                                    │
│ ...                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│ }                                                                                                                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│ The recurrence PHI node `%for` has two incoming values: `%for.start` from the preheader (`entry`) and `%for.next` from the loop latch.                                                   │
│ The instruction `%for.next = and i8 %for.start, -1` is loop-invariant. Since `%for.start` is an `i8`, `and i8 %for.start, -1` is equivalent to `%for.start`.                             │
│ So, after simplification, the PHI node effectively becomes `phi i8 [ %for.start, %entry ], [ %for.start, %loop ]`. This means `%for` is a loop-invariant value, always equal to          │
│ `%for.start`.                                                                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The loop vectorizer should recognize this as a loop-invariant recurrence and handle it correctly. The crash suggests it doesn't. The error message mentions a `shufflevector` not        │
│ dominating a `phi` use, which is a classic sign of incorrect instruction placement during vectorization.                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The problem likely lies in how the vectorizer handles the value of the recurrence for the next iteration. For a normal recurrence, this value is computed inside the loop. For this      │
│ specific case, the value is loop-invariant.                                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Looking at the `LoopVectorize.cpp` code, specifically `LoopVectorizationPlanner::planLoop`, there's a section that handles recurrences. A key part is identifying the instruction that   │
│ provides the value for the next iteration of the recurrence PHI. This is done by `RecurrenceDescriptor::getRecurrenceBinOp`.                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ In `getRecurrenceBinOp`, there's logic to trace back from the recurrence PHI's incoming value. It checks if the instruction is a binary operator, a cast, or a select. If the            │
│ instruction is loop-invariant, it should be handled as a special case.                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The current logic in `getRecurrenceBinOp` seems to have a flaw. When it encounters a loop-invariant instruction that provides the recurrence value, it correctly identifies it but then  │
│ proceeds to set `Rdx.RecurKind` to `RecurKind::None`. This seems incorrect. If it's a loop-invariant recurrence, it should probably be classified as a specific kind of recurrence, not  │
│ as "not a recurrence". This misclassification likely leads to incorrect code generation later on.                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ A potential fix is to modify `getRecurrenceBinOp` to correctly handle this case. When a loop-invariant instruction is found to be the source of the recurrence's next value, we should   │
│ not reset the recurrence kind. Instead, we should just stop traversing up the use-def chain, as we've found the loop-invariant source. The instruction itself is the binary operator we  │
│ are looking for in a sense, even if it's not a typical arithmetic op.                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will apply a patch that modifies `LoopVectorizationPlanner::getRecurrenceBinOp`. The change will be to remove the line `Rdx.RecurKind = RecurKind::None;` and just `break;` from the   │
│ loop when a loop-invariant instruction is encountered. This ensures that the recurrence is still treated as such, but with a loop-invariant feedback value, which should allow the rest  │
│ of the vectorizer to handle it correctly.                                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i '10019s/Rdx.RecurKind = RecurKind::None;/break;/' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                                                                                 │
